50|$|Since {{mass media}} {{traditionally}} was limited solely to print media, naturally the monitoring was also limited to these media. The world's first press <b>clipping</b> <b>agency</b> {{was established in}} London in 1852 by a Polish newsagent named Romeike. Actors, writers, musicians and artists would visit his shop to look for articles about themselves in his Continental stock. It was then that Romeike realised that he could turn this into a profitable business. The agency later became Romeike & Curtice and {{is now part of}} Cision.|$|E
40|$|The {{bulk of the}} {{collection}} consists of clippings on Tugendreich and of newpaper articles by Tugendreich, some of which bear the stamps of a news <b>clipping</b> <b>agency</b> (Büro für Zeitungsabschnitte). Also included {{are a couple of}} longer periodical essays on pediatric health advocacy, a photocopy of Tugendreich's curriculum vitae and bibliography of published works, some original correspondence with government authorities and committees regarding infant health advocacy, and a pamphlet on an infant welfare conference. Tugendreich was a physician, born 1876, professionally active in Berlin and specializing in pediatrics and public hygiene, known for his advocacy to reduce infant mortality and to expand access to pediatric health services. The original German-language inventory is available in the folder. Processed for digitization bydigitize...|$|E
